    Andrei Neagoie and 1 other made an announcement: Helloooooo everyone! It’s that time again for some community updates: 1. Coding Challenge #6 is all done! You can see all of the submissions right here. Have you not finished it yet? Don’t worry, you can still read about the challenge and partake in the fun by comparing your answers to everyone else. It has also become part of the official course (Lecture 135) 2. #howigotstarted: The big goal of this course is to get people hired as web developers. In an effort to constantly improve your experience, I thought we would do something fun and I will get the ball rolling - If you go to Discord’s #job-hunting channel, I have shared my story of how I got my very first developer job. I encourage all of you who are already working as developers to share your story on how you got started with #howigotstarted in the text. This way, future students can search this term on Discord search bar and have a source of great stories, tips, advice, and inspiration of how they can one day become web developers as well.  3. I wrote a new blog post recently with some excellent free resources that you will enjoy. You can read it here: https://hackernoon.com/dont-be-a-junior-developer-the-roadmap-9fde5cf384bb 4. More organized look to Discord! (See lecture 3 for invite link) You may have noticed a few new categories on the Discord server. In order to keep conversations organized (we have over 100 students joining Discord everyday), the management team and I have created a fresher look so you can find the topics that interest you. The Discord server was just created 2 months ago and we have close to 10,000 developers online already…I check it regularly not because I have to answer questions, but also because it has become a great source of information and a great way to see topics and articles that people share to stay up to date in the industry. Go have a look! (Ps behind the scenes the @Management Team works really hard daily to make sure everything works “just right”. Give them a big thank you when you get a chance. They do 99.999% of the work behind the scenes selflessly while they make me feel useless) 5. Random but somewhat relevant things:- I did a recent poll on twitter and many of you have suggested that the next course you would like to see is Machine Learning for Web Developers- Coding Challenge #7 is coming up and it may involve you working in teams (hint hint)… stay tuned!- Locals (on Discord) discussions during World Cup games have been really fun to watch. As always, thank you for being part of this community and staying motivated to finish the course. It has been great seeing this tight knit community grow from our tiny group of 50 less than 7 months ago. I hope you keep pushing through the highs and lows of becoming a successful web developer. It will all be worth it in the end. As I said in the introduction video, no one starts as an expert!
